definition.value: A rac-1-monoacylglycerol composed of equal amounts of 1-arachidonoyl-sn-glycerol and  3-arachidonoyl-sn-glycerol.
A  2,3-diacyl-sn-glycerol where oleoyl and arachidonoyl form the 2- and 3-acyl groups respectively.
A rac-1,2-diglyceride that is composed of equal amounts of 1-arachidonoyl-2-oleoyl-sn-glycerol and  2-oleoyl-3-arachidonoyl-sn-glycerol.
A 1-acyl-sn-glycerol where alpha-linolenoyl is the 1-acyl group.
A  3-acyl-sn-glycerol where alpha-linolenoyl is the 3-acyl group.
A rac-1-monoacylglycerol that is composed of equal amounts of 1-alpha-linolenoyl-sn-glycerol and 3-alpha-linolenoyl-sn-glycerol.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycerol where alpha-linolenoyl and oleoyl form the 1- and 2-acyl groups respectively.
A  1,2-diglyceride with lauroyl and oleoyl as the two acyl groups.
A  2,3-diacyl-sn-glycerol where oleoyl and alpha-linolenoyl form the 2- and 3-acyl groups respectively.
A  rac-1,2-diglyceride that is composed of equal amounts of 2-oleoyl-3-alpha-linolenoyl-sn-glycerol and 1-alpha-linolenoyl-2-oleoyl-sn-glycerol.
A 1,2-diglyceride with myristoyl and oleoyl as the two acyl groups.
The S-enantiomer of 1,2-dioleoyl-3-palmitoylglycerol.
A palmitate ester resulting from the formal condensation of palmitic acid with palmityl alcohol. It is used as a thickener and emollient in cosmetics.
A 1,2-diglyceride with palmitoyl and oleoyl as the two acyl groups.
A glycol that is hexadecane which is substituted by hydroxy groups at positions 1 and 2.
A palmitate ester resulting from the formal condensation of palmitic acid with 1,2-hexadecandiol.
A C-glycosyl compound that is apigenin substituted at positions 6 and 8 by alpha-L-arabinopyranosyl and beta-D-glucosyl residues respectively.
A 1,2-diglyceride with stearoyl and oleoyl as the acyl groups.
A 4-amino-1,2-oxazolidin-3-one that has S configuration. An antibiotic isolated from Erwinia uredovora.
An oligonucleotide comprised of ten thymidine residues connected via 3'->5' phosphodiester linkages.
An EC 5.1.1.* (racemases acting on amino acids and derivatives) inhibitor that interferes with the action of alanine racemase (EC 5.1.1.1).
An enzyme inhibitor that inhibits the action of an isomerase (EC 5.*.*.*).
An oligonucleotide comprised of eight thymidine residues connected via 3'->5' phosphodiester linkages.
An acid--amino-acid ligase inhibitor that inhibits the action of a D-alanine--D-alanine ligase (EC 6.3.2.4).
An acid--amino-acid ligase inhibitor that inhibits the action of a glutamate--cysteine ligase (EC 6.3.2.2)

A cyclic dicarboxylic anhydride that is 5,6,7,8,9,10-hexahydro-1H-cyclonona[c]furan-1,3(4H)-dione substituted by an ethylidene group at position 9, hydroxy groups at position 5 and 8, a propyl group at position 4 and an oxo group at position 6.
A ligase inhibitor that interferes with the action of a C-N bond-forming ligase (EC 6.3.*.*).
An oligonucleotide comprised of four thymidine residues connected via 3'->5' phosphodiester linkages.

Any enzyme inhibitor that interferes with the action of a ligase (EC 6.*.*.*). Ligases are enzymes that catalyse the joining of two molecules with concomitant hydrolysis of the diphosphate bond in ATP or a similar triphosphate.
A ligase inhibitor that interferes with the action of a C-C bond-forming ligase (EC 6.4.*.*).
A ligase inhibitor which inhibits the action of a phosphoric ester bond-forming ligase (EC 6.5.*.*).
A carboxamide that is a hydroxamic acid in which the hydrogen of the hydroxy group is replaced by an organyl group.
A polynucleotide comprised of 5-bromo-2'-deoxyuridine units connected via 3'->5' phosphodiester linkages.
A wax ester resulting from the formal condensation of both the hydroxy groups of  hexadecane-1,2-diol with two molecules of  palmitic acid.
A 1,2-diglyceride with linolenoyl and oleoyl as the two acyl groups.
A 1-monoglyceride that has alpha-linolenoyl as the acyl group.
A 1,2-diglyceride where arachidonoyl and oleoyl are the two acyl groups.
A 1-monoglyceride where the acyl group is arachidonoyl.
A 1,2-diglyceride where linoleoyl and oleoyl are the two acyl groups.
A hydroperoxy fatty acid obtained by the formal substitution of a hydrogen at position 10 of (8E,12Z,15Z)-octadeca-10,12,15-trienoic acid by a hydroperoxy group (the 10S stereoisomer).
An organic cation obtained by protonation of the five amino groups of any gentamicin C.
An organic cation obtained by protonation of the four amino groups of any N(3')-acetylgentamicin C.

A proanthocyanidin that is (+)-catechin and (-)-epicatechin units joined by a bond between positions 4 and 6' respectively in an alpha-configuration. Procyanidin B8 is found in acorn and is present in fruit and leaves of blackberry (Rubus fruticosus), raspberry (Rubus idaeus) and cowberry (Vaccinium vitis idaea). It can be also found in grape seeds and in beer.

A proanthocyanidin consisting of two molecules of (+)-catechin joined by a bond between positions 4 and 6' in alpha-configuration. Procyanidin B6 is isolated from leaves and fruit of cowberry Vaccinium vitis-idaea and other plants. It can also be found in grape seeds and in beer.
A wax ester obtained by the formal condensation of the carboxy group of oleic acid with the hydroxy group of decanol.

A proanthocyanidin  consisting of two molecules of (-)-epicatechin joined by a bond between positions 4 and 6' in beta-configuration. It can be found in grape seeds, in Hibiscus cannabinus (kenaf) root and bark, in apple and in cacao.
A wax ester obtained by the formal condensation of hexadecan-1-ol with oleic acid.
A member of the class of hexadecen-1-ols that is hexadecanol containing a double bond located at position 9 (the Z-geoisomer).
A wax ester obtained by the formal condensation of hexadecen-1-ol with  oleic acid.
A wax ester obtained by the formal condensation of oleic acid with stearyl alcohol.
